==Merged second translation== {{Infobox religious building| religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | name = Kotohira Shrine | image = [[File:Kuji-konpira.jpg|thumbnail|250px|Shrine grounds]] | coordinates = {{Coord|40|12|11.5|N|141|47|28.7|E|scale:25000_region:JP-03_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | location = Minatocho 13-90, Kuji City, Iwate Prefecture, Japan | deity = {{ill|Ōmononushi|ja|大物主命|1=Ōmononushi|lt=Ōmononushi-no-Mikoto|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmononushi|13=User:Immanuelle/Ōmononushi|qq=}} ([[Konpira Gongen]]) {{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} | founded = 1718 {{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} | festivals = August 10 {{Citation needed|date=October 2015}} }}
'''Kotohira Shrine''' ({{nihongo|金刀比羅神社|ことひらじんじゃ}}) is a [[Shinto shrine]] located in {{ill|Kuji City|ja|久慈市|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuji City|qq=}}, Iwate Prefecture, Japan. It is affectionately known as {{nihongo|"Konpira-san"|こんぴらさん}}.
The shrine is situated on a hill, offering a scenic view of Kuji Bay. It is designated as a {{ill|tsunami evacuation site|ja|津波避難施設|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/tsunami evacuation site|qq=}},<ref>{{Cite web|title=津波ハザードマップ|url=http://bousai.city.kuji.iwate.jp/contents/pc/pdf/hazardmap/jishintsunami/07.pdf|format=PDF|publisher=Kuji City|accessdate=2015-10-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304213804/http://bousai.city.kuji.iwate.jp/contents/pc/pdf/hazardmap/jishintsunami/07.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04}}</ref> and during the {{nihongo|[[2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami|Great East Japan Earthquake]]|東日本大震災}} on March 11, 2011, many people sought refuge there.
